text: *a, b, *c = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5)*    # int, int, list and tuple         print(a)    # 1         print(b)    # 2         print(c)    # [3, 4, 5]  *a, _, *c = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5)*         print(a)    # 1         print(_)    # 2         print(c)    #[3, 4, 5]  *a, b, *c, d = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5)*         print(a)    # 1         print(b)    # 2         print(c)    # [3, 4, 5]         print(d)    # 5  *a, b, *_, d = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5)*         print(a)    # 1         print(b)    # 2         print(_)    # [3, 4, 5]         print(d)    # 5   So, the asterisk works as expected. But that underscore seems to work like any other variable. Except that you're propably less likely to accidentally use it for something.

author: @csathys2
text: Hi Cory, just a few minutes into this video, your first 2 tips, use of ternary condition and enumerates,  led me to come up with this class that would pretty much "act" like a substring on a list of elements. For example, if you wanted to just extract certain elements of a string. Full code is here: class mylib():          def __init__(self, list_a, start, end):         self.list_a = list_a         self.start = start         self.end = end              def getSubset(self):         names = self.list_a         en=enumerate(names)         startpos=self.start         endpos=self.end         c=[] # initialize a new list         for idx, name in en:             # Append only if our criteria is satisfied.             c.append(name) if (idx >= startpos and idx <= endpos) else ''# print(str(idx)+' Failed')         return(c) Here is how you call it: nameslist=['Corey','Chris','A','b','Z','more','and more'] nl=mylib(nameslist,6,7) nl.getSubset()  I'm continuing to watch rest of it.

author: @NyscanRohid
text: For the `zip` example, just use an index. There's nothing wrong with it, it's not unintuitive, and it's one less useless filtering function you have to memorize. I get it that python wants to be clean and efficient, but it just seems like bells and whistles at this point. The whole point of having parallel arrays is so that you can index through them in parallel, which means they already have convenience built in to their design; you don't need to add more convoluted convenience. Suppose I'm your client who isn't as savvy with python, and I need to read your code to see what it does, and it tells me to go look up `zip`, because you need it to do something as stupidly simple as indexing through two arrays in parallel. It's not helpful, it's annoying.

author: @Acecool
text: Good call on the underscores - I wasn't aware of that. What I typically do is align the = on my code, then for numbers I just add spaces to the beginning so the numbers line up where they should be. The unpacking with *_ is useful too, can be used for shifting during recursion, and other things. I usually just pass through to the function though by having 2 unpacked args and then having a varargs or keyed varargs arg after to contain the rest.  Instead of setattr and getattr ( you forgot to add in a default - I would always recommend setting it to nil in the code if you aren't going to use it so someone looking at it will know that something can go there - even though it is optional, having it defined as nil lets someone who isn't as familiar use it... you could even set it as a non-existant variable name and call it default ).  there is another thing called properties. This lets you set up these accessors quickly and easily. I prefer function names, so I set up an accessor helper object which creates both. so I can do 1 line of code in an object such as class BaseBlah: pass, class Base( BaseBlah ): __x = Accessor( BaseBlah, 'x', 'X', TYPE_FLOAT, default = 0.0 ) and y, and z.. and create blah.GetX( ), blah.SetX( 'test' ) which is ignored because it isn't a number, blah.x = 123.00 which goes through the setter property.. The one problem is I have to create an empty base so that I can define it within the object, but it ends up looking decently clean except that empty class base, and I can set up a lot of advanced restrictions for the accessors such as restricting a data-type to one or many, a value to one or many, defining has helpers, adders, tostring functions, and more.  I use __x which links to the accessor object so changes can be made. _x is the raw data. .x goes through the property. So I can set a default value and _x can be nil, but .x will return 0.0.  Accessors are helpful.

author: @ariearie5054
text: Great vid man. There is one more thing I would add to the unpacking tip. I'm definately not an expert but i ran into this trick the other day. If you have a function that takes e.g. 2 inputs as integers (x, y) and you get the x, y values in Tuples (x, y) or lists, it wont take it as arguement since input x would correspond to the Tuple (x, y). You could use the asterix *(x, y) to unpack it and pass the Tuple into the function.

text: Quick question.  Still super new to Python.  I haven't been in the dev game for roughly 10 years and Python is my first and only experience with an interpretive language.  All prior experience was within the Visual Studio .NET framework, specifically with the languages VB & C#.  Firstly, I absolutely LOVE Python.  Like too much.  It feels like how programming was always meant to be.  Anyway:  though I have significant experience in other languages, this is my first time taking the self-taught approach to learning a new language.  Besides that, its been nearly a decade since I did any legitimate writing.  So I'm coming at this from a fresh perspective.  I can see these techniques being useful.  Even when you were explaining advanced unpacking techniques, I can still see the utility.  I adore the utility of the zip function and the enumerate function.  I love the ability to set and get attributes on the fly.  And though not all techniques are useful at all times, that's just the way programming is.  Some use cases are much more narrow than others.  My question is this:  is there a specific resource online somewhere that has quick categorized access to all of these niche functions hidden within Python?  I'm still not quite familiar with modern programming community tools like GitHub or Stack Overflow or Jupyter, etc.  And I'm still not entirely grounded in Python enough to know what libraries are critical, what libraries are superior, what is and what isn't within the core Python library, the utility of Anaconda or Iron Python, etc.  Still soaking up new information.  As it stands I have no problem writing quick effective scripts in Python but when it comes to pre-built, pre-packaged utility, I don't know where to look and why.  So if anyone has pointers for specific tools and use cases for them, I'd very much appreciate it.  Phenomenal video, btw.  Much love.

author: @garybloomlaw
text: Regarding 'zip'... In conjunction with slices, it's a great way to "pair up" elements in a list or tuple. So, if you have nums = (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5), you can use zip(nums[::2], nums[1::2]) to get ((0, 1), (2, 3), (4, 5))

text: # test calling one fuction from another and termination based on user input import sys def chumy():     """Print the words 'I have a wooden leg'     and message exit_question function"""     print("I have a wooden leg")     exit_question() def exit_question():     """Ask user if they want to exit program     and return answer to gumy or chumy function"""     answer = ("yes", "no")     response = ""     while response not in answer:         response = input("Do you want to exit this program ")         response = response.lower()         if response == "no":             print("your answer is ", response, "So we do the function gumy()")             gumy()         elif response == "yes":             print("your answer is ", response, "So we do the terminate function now")             terminate()         else:             print("you did not say yes or no!")             print("In fact you said ", response, "So we do the function chumy()")             chumy() def terminate():     """cause code controled termination"""     sys.stderr.write('terminate function called from code scipt!\n')     raise SystemExit(1)   def gumy():     """Print the words 'I am gumy'     and message exit_question function"""     print("I am gumy")     exit_question()     # # test run code gumy() chumy() user will need to make sure the indentation is correct!

author: @pythonprojectsforwindows6795
text: Tip for OOP __iter__, __next__ methods and StopIteration class rangep:     '''Pure Python sequence type container. Version 1.05     index starts at 0     Replaces builtin range() type constructor'''     def __init__(self, stop, start=0):         self.stop = stop         self.start = start     def __iter__(self):         self.count = self.start         return self     def __next__(self):         if self.count < self.stop:             next = self.count             self.count += 1             return next         else:             raise StopIteration  container = rangep(1_000_000) for item in container:     print(item)
